Context("LimitedNumeric");
Context()->{format}{number} = "%f#";
#Context()->{format}{number} = "%9d";

$int00 = random(2,9,1);
$int01 = random(2,9,1);
$product0 = $int00*$int01;

$int10 = $int00/10;
$int11 = $int01/10;
$product1 = Real($int10*$int11);

$int20 = $int00;
$power21 = random(1,4,1);
$int21 = $int01/10**$power21;
$product2 = Real($int20*$int21);

$power30 = random(2,3,1);
$int30 = $int00/10**$power30;
$power31 = random(1,3,1);
$int31 = $int01/10**$power31;
$product3 = Real($int30*$int31);

##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML

Calculate the following without using a calculator:

a.    [`` [$int10] \cdot [$int11] = ``] [___________]{$product1}

a.    [`` [$int20] \cdot [$int21] = ``] [___________]{$product2}

a.    [`` [$int30] \cdot [$int31] = ``] [___________]{$product3}

END_PGML

##############################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

Since [`[$int00] \cdot [$int01] = [$product0] `], we can calculate [` [$int10] \cdot [$int11] `] in this way:

    [`` 
\begin{aligned}[t]
   &\phantom{{}=} [$int10] \cdot [$int11] \\
   &= \frac{[$int00]}{10} \cdot \frac{[$int01]}{10} \\
   &= \frac{[$int00] \cdot [$int01]}{10 \cdot 10} \\
   &= \frac{[$product0]}{100} \\
   &= [$product1]
\end{aligned}
    ``]

Once we understand the math, we can use this shortcut to calculate the above problem:

1. From [`[$int00]`] to [`[$int10]`], the decimal point moved to the left once.
2. From [`[$int01]`] to [`[$int11]`], the decimal point moved to the left once.
3. Since [`[$int00] \cdot [$int01] = [$product0] `], to calculate [`[$int10] \cdot [$int11] `], we move the decimal point of [`[$product0]`] to the left twice, and we have: [`[$int10] \cdot [$int11] = [$product1] `].

*Solutions:*

a.    [``[$int10] \cdot [$int11] = [$product1] ``]
a.    [``[$int20] \cdot [$int21] = [$product2] ``]
a.    [``[$int30] \cdot [$int31] = [$product3] ``]


END_PGML_SOLUTION

